<DOC><DOCNO> DOE2-37-0745 </DOCNO><TEXT>Increasing emphasis in complex systems on higher levels of automationcan cause human factors problems, especially if automation reduces therole and responsibility of people, at least of those who operate systemequipment and software. This paper describes the following four potentialproblems: operators' perception of subservience to machines, improperintroduction of automation, poor human factors engineering of human-computerinterfaces, and loss of skills to cope with rare or unanticipated events.Two examples presented to demonstrate improper introduction of automationconcern modifications in the control rooms of nuclear power plants. 14refs.</TEXT></DOC>